urls.title: When were 300 baud modems used up until
urls.description: 300 baud modems (equivalent to 300 bits per second, based on standards like the Bell 103) were introduced commercially in 1962 by AT&T and became the dominant speed for early dial-up data transmission through the 1960s and 1970s. They remained widely used in consumer and hobbyist contexts—such as early personal computers, bulletin board systems (BBSes), and online services—into the early to mid-1980s. During this period, many systems and modems supported 300 baud as the default or fallback speed. By the mid-1980s, faster modems (1200 baud in the early 1980s, then 2400 baud by the late 1980s) became affordable and prevalent, largely replacing 300 baud for most users due to better performance for file transfers and interactive use. However, 300 baud compatibility persisted as a fallback mode in higher-speed modems well into the 1990s and beyond, for connecting to legacy systems or poor phone lines. The image's claim about successive tribal control of Plains land is largely accurate historically. The Arikara arrived by AD 1500, followed by the Cheyenne, Crow, Kiowa, and Arapaho, and the Lakota (also known as Sioux) arrived from Minnesota in the 18th century and displaced the other tribes that lived there, who eventually moved to what became known as the Western United States.  After conquering the Cheyenne in 1776, the Lakota took the territory of the Black Hills, which became central to their culture. Regarding enslavement: Native American groups often enslaved war captives, whom they primarily used for small-scale labor, and some Native American tribes held war captives as slaves prior to and during European colonization. However, this practice differed fundamentally from chattel slavery. Outsider captives taken in warfare might be adopted into the tribe to replace lost kinsmen; they might be executed, in revenge for lost kinsmen; or they might become slaves. The meme's framing is misleading, though. Intertribal conflicts occurred on vastly different scales than European/American colonization, which involved systematic land seizure, disease, broken treaties, forced removals, and industrialized violence. The United States government illegally seized the Black Hills from the Sioux Nation in 1876, and the land was pledged to the Sioux Nation in the Treaty of Fort Laramie, but the United States illegally seized the land and nullified the treaty without the tribe's consent.

urls.title: Who have beared the burden if Trump’s tariffs during his second term?
urls.description: Based on economic analyses and data from 2025, the burden of tariffs implemented during Donald Trump's second term has primarily been borne by American businesses (importers and retailers) and consumers, rather than foreign exporters or governments as often claimed. US importers initially absorb a significant portion of the costs through reduced profit margins, but these are increasingly passed on to consumers in the form of higher prices for imported goods and domestic alternatives. Over time, the share shifts: for instance, by mid-2025, importers bore around 64% of the tariff costs shortly after implementation, with foreign exporters absorbing about 14% via lower export prices and US consumers facing 22% through price hikes. By October 2025, this evolved to importers at 27%, exporters at 18%, and consumers at 55%, with projections for 2026 estimating consumers bearing roughly 67% of the total burden.
